author: @LANACION
title: Volvió una dura guerra de laboratorios por el negocio de la vacuna antiaftosa - LA NACION
text:
Un laboratorio reanudó una disputa con otro por la vacuna antiaftosa. Se trata de Centro Diagnóstico Veterinario (CDV), que en un comunicado, aunque sin mencionarlo explícitamente, acusó a Tecnovax de aplicar “cuestionables maniobras”. Esta última empresa viene fomentando la importación de la vacuna desde Brasil y de hecho acaba de ingresar dosis al país para su control oficial. Si bien CDV no nombró a Tecnovax en su comunicado, desde la empresa indicaron a LA NACION que la mención es precisamente a esa compañía. El negocio de la vacuna es de unos US$100 millones por año. En rigor, detrás de esta cuestión hay una pelea más profunda: Tecnovax, que a comienzos de año empezó a batallar que en la Argentina supuestamente la vacuna llegaba a los productores a valores más caros que en la región, logró la simpatía oficial y terminó consiguiendo que el Gobierno, a través del vocero presidencial, Manuel Adorni , anunciara la modificación de una normativa para que se facilitara la importación del producto.
En rigor, el Senasa modificó una norma para habilitar la dosis bivalente. Tecnovax, vale recordar, en julio pasado había denunciado ante la Comisión Nacional de Defensa de la Competencia a Biogénesis Bagó y CDV por supuesta “ cartelización y abuso de posición dominante” .
“A LA VANGUARDIA”: CIENTÍFICOS ARGENTINOS LOGRARON EL NACIMIENTO DE LOS PRIMEROS CINCO CABALLOS EDITADOS GENÉTICAMENTE DEL MUNDO En la carrera por la nueva vacuna, según pudo saber este medio, ante los exigentes controles y pruebas del Senasa son Biogénesis Bagó y CDV quienes están más avanzados. Esta semana, en tanto, en sus redes Tecnovax difundió el siguiente mensaje: “Llegó el primer lote de vacunas contra la aftosa! Después de casi seis meses de trabajo, ingresamos nuestra primera serie de la vacuna antiaftosa para su control oficial”.
“En un contexto donde la sanidad animal es crucial para mantener la posición de la Argentina como uno de los principales exportadores de carne a nivel mundial, observamos cuestionables maniobras que no solo ponen en riesgo el estatus sanitario del país, sino también la confianza de los productores y mercados internacionales”, comenzó CDV en su comunicado.
CDV: "Observamos cuestionables maniobras que no solo ponen en riesgo el estatus sanitario del país, sino también la confianza de los productores y mercados internacionales” SENASA

author: news@lincolnshireecho.co.uk (Joe Griffin)
title: RAF Scampton: Government warns of 'tensions' between Sunni and Shia Muslims on base in now-deleted report
text: A new [RAF Scampton](https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/all-about/raf-scampton) report which was published by the Home Office and removed days later has highlighted the possible tensions between two Muslim groups that would be housed on the former base. An 'equality impact assessment' was published on the UK Government website on Wednesday, December 27 and it revealed some new details about the proposed asylum centre at the former home of the Dambusters. The report, which was removed on December 29 due to being 'published in error', states that some of the population of asylum seekers would be split between Sunni and Shia Islam sects which "could potentially cause tensions" on the base. It adds that "consideration will be given to separate worship areas" and the mixing of these populations will be monitored. Religion is the only characteristic group that the Home Office considers to have 'medium' potential for a positive/negative impact. All other characteristic groups listed in the report, including age, sex and disability, were considered to have a 'low' potential for a positive/negative impact. Poll - [Are you worried about the RAF asylum seekers plans?](https://xd.wayin.com/display/container/dc/681b1626-eb89-4dcc-871e-0201734dcdec?mode=responsive&scrolling=no) A recent High Court ruling deemed that up to 2,000 asylum seekers could be lawfully housed at RAF Scampton despite West Lindsey District Council's attempts to stop the plans. WLDC has since announced that it intends to appeal the ruling and continue the fight against housing asylum seekers at the former base. Class Q planning permission was obtained by the Home Office in April 2023 and is due to expire on April 13, 2024. The Home Office revealed in the equality impact report that it intends to seek planning permission under a Special Development Order to cover temporary planning permission for a further three years. Within the now deleted government report, it explains that free shuttle bus transport, in collaboration with Lincolnshire County Council and the City of Lincoln Council, will be provided to asylum seekers to travel to local urban areas, including Lincoln, for recreational purposes and other purposes. This includes travel to religious buildings to practise their religion or belief. The report states that the asylum seekers, who will come straight from Manston immigration centre in Kent, can leave the Scampton site for up to seven days at a time unless a reasonable explanation is given for their prolonged absence. Asylum seekers will be able to interact with local people and make use of local amenities and facilities located outside of the site. However, the Home Office report states that the asylum seekers will be provided with enough services and facilities on-site that they will not need to leave to access them. One section of the report reads: "Asylum seekers accommodated at Scampton will be provided with dietary and culturally and religiously appropriate meals, facilities to use on site e.g. Wi-Fi, TV room, gymnasium, laundry room with washers and driers, provision for practising their faith including religious observance and regular organised indoor and outdoor activities. "Additional facilities, including sports facilities and social spaces, will be brought online as the site develops and when it reaches its maximum capacity." Asylum seekers will also be provided with mobile phones and laptops on-site on request which can be used to maintain contact with other parties including their legal representation and Migrant Help. Those housed at the former RAF base will have access to free NHS healthcare. Primary GP-led healthcare will be provided on site from the day of arrival of the first cohort of asylum seekers, including dedicated isolation rooms for those with suspected/confirmed contagious diseases. The maximum length of stay for individual asylum seekers on site will be nine months, except when the Home Secretary is unable to find "suitable onward dispersal accommodation". The report also addresses potential protests from three groups which include: Local residents and politicians who object to the use of the site for accommodation which had been earmarked by the West Lindsey District for a £300m redevelopment programme. Pro-immigration groups who have concerns about the perceived conditions on the site. Anti-immigration groups who object to the housing of asylum seekers or their arrival in the country. A section of the report reads: "Experience from Wethersfield and Portland is that protests reduce once the site has opened, but it is recognised that this may not be the case at every site, including Scampton. Site security and operations staff liaise with the police on an almost daily (primarily ad-hoc) basis and police response to protests has been calibrated to ensure there is no escalation of tensions. "We continue to work closely with the police to minimise disruption, including after the site becomes operational." Lincolnshire Police are providing three dedicated Community Relation officers to reassure and safeguard the local community, asylum seekers, and workers on, as well as visitors to, the site to provide a more "visible presence". It has been agreed that screened fencing will be put in place to restrict the sight of Pollyplatt Primary School from the site. A date has still not been confirmed for the arrival of the first 30 asylum seekers, which will be gradually increased over time. All asylum seekers will be males aged between 18 and 65 and could come from a number of countries including: Iraq, Iran, Albania, Eritrea, Pakistan, Nigeria, China, Afghanistan, Syria, Sudan, El Salvador, and Ethiopia. The Home Office has been approached for comment but did not respond by the time of publication.

author: Radio-Canada
title: La Nouvelle-Zélande subit l’élimination en rugby à 7 | Jeux olympiques | Radio-Canada
text: [Regardez les Jeux olympiques en direct sur ICI Télé dès le 26 juillet](/jeux-olympiques/diffusion/tele) En ondes tous les jours de 6 h à 1 h HAE le lendemain Vous naviguez sur le site de Radio-Canada En ondes tous les jours de 6 h à 1 h HAE le lendemain Les Jeux de Paris ne sont même pas encore officiellement commencés que l’on connaît déjà les quatre équipes masculines qui se battront pour une médaille en rugby à 7. L’Afrique du Sud, la France, l’Australie et les îles Fidji ont accédé au carré d'as. La Nouvelle-Zélande et l’Afrique du Sud ont donné aux amateurs de rugby un premier quart de finale très chaudement disputé. Les Sud-Africains, classés 8es et entrés en phase éliminatoire par la porte arrière, ont décroché une victoire de 14-7. C’est sur ce pointage que s’est conclue la première demie. Les All Blacks ont cogné à la porte de leurs adversaires à de multiples reprises, dont au moins cinq fois dans la dernière minute de jeu, sans obtenir un essai pour égaliser. Selvyn Davids et Tritant Leyds ont marqué pour l’Afrique du Sud. La réplique néo-zélandaise est venue de Moses Leo. C’est une amère défaite pour la Nouvelle-Zélande, qui avait remporté la médaille d’argent, à Tokyo, en 2021. Les champions olympiques ont pour leur part eu chaud, très chaud, jeudi, mais les îles Fidji ont finalement remporté une victoire de 19-15 face à l’Irlande. Les Fidjiens n’ont pris que 43 secondes pour prendre les commandes dans leur match face aux Irlandais. Iowane Teba a marqué un premier essai pour les champions, mais la suite a été ardue pour les médaillés d’or en titre. Chay Mullins a donné la réplique pour l’Irlande avec deux essais qui ont nécessité la reprise vidéo avant d’être accordés. Zac Ward en a ajouté un. Par deux fois, leur coéquipier Mark Roche a toutefois raté les conversions qui ont suivi. Ces points, les Irlandais les regretteront plus tard, malgré leur avance de 15-12 à ce moment. Les Îles Fidji ont repris leur sens avec Waisera Nacuqu qui a redonné les commandes à sa nation, qui a ensuite tenu bon pour l’emporter. Plus de peur que de mal pour les Fidjiens qui auront donc encore l’occasion de défendre leur titre. Le duel France-Argentine qui a suivi n’avait rien à envier à cette rencontre. Les deux pays s’affrontaient dans une reprise de la finale du plus récent Championnat du monde disputé en juin, à Madrid. Les Bleus en sont sortis vainqueurs, encore, cette fois par la marque de 26-14. La France n’a voulu laisser aucun doute et aucune chance à ses adversaires, menant 21-0 après la première demie. Galvanisés par une foule acquise au Stade de France, Andy Timo et Aaron Grandidier (deux fois) ont marqué des essais. Mais, Jordan Secho a mis son équipe dans le trouble en milieu de deuxième période lorsqu’il a écopé d’un carton jaune qui a privé la France d’un joueur pendant deux minutes. L’Argentine en a profité pour resserrer l’écart à 21-14, mais a manqué de temps. Antoine Dupont a mis le dernier clou dans le cercueil argentin en marquant en toute fin de rencontre. Le parcours français en phase préliminaire avait été chaotique. L’équipe s’était inclinée 19-12 devant les îles Fidji, avant de faire match nul 12-12 avec les États-Unis, puis de remporter une victoire serrée de 19-12 sur l’Uruguay. On se demandait si la rencontre entre l’Australie et les États-Unis réservait un autre grand cru après tant de rencontres de grande qualité. Cela n'a pas été le cas. Les Australiens ont facilement vaincu les Américains 18-0, manquant de finition à de multiples occasions. James Turner et Corey Toole ont inscrit des essais en première demie, avant que Maurice Longbottom ne marque une pénalité en deuxième demie, puis un essai dans les arrêts de jeu. Il s'agit de la première fois que les Australiens atteignent les demi-finales, eux qui avaient été éliminés en quarts en 2016 et en 2021. Le rugby à 7 prendra une pause vendredi pour la cérémonie d’ouverture. La compétition reprendra samedi. La France fera face à l’Afrique du Sud en demi-finales, tandis que les Îles Fidji rencontreront l’Australie pour accéder à la finale olympique.

author: Sunday
title: WHO and partners deliver aid to two Gaza hospitals in high-risk missions | Scoop News
text: WHO and partners deliver aid to two Gaza hospitals in high-risk missions The World Health Organization (WHO) and partners delivered fuel and other essential supplies to two hospitals in northern and southern Gaza this week, the UN agency reported on Wednesday. Teams that undertook [the high-risk missions ](https://www.who.int/news/item/27-12-2023-who-teams-deliver-supplies-to-hospitals-in-northern-and-southern-gaza)witnessed intense hostilities in their vicinity, as well as high patient loads and overcrowding caused by people seeking refuge. They also reported that food needs remain dire across the enclave, which is impacting operations, with hungry people stopping convoys in hopes of finding something to eat. [WHO](http://www.who.int/en/) Director-General Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus issued a fresh call for the international community to “take urgent steps to alleviate the grave peril facing the population of Gaza and jeopardizing the ability of humanitarian workers to help people with terrible injuries, acute hunger, and at severe risk of disease.” Hospitals sheltering thousands Personnel visited two hospitals on Tuesday - Al-Shifa in northern Gaza and Al-Amal Palestine Red Crescent Society (PRCS) in the south. Both hospitals also serve as shelters for people displaced by the ongoing conflict, with 50,000 reported at Al-Shifa and 14,000 at Al-Amal. At Al-Shifa, WHO delivered fuel to keep essential health services running. Staff also brought medical supplies, alongside UN children’s agency [UNICEF](https://www.unicef.org/). In support of NGO partner the World Central Kitchen, WHO also delivered materials that will support a kitchen at the hospital. The Gaza Central Drug Store also received medical supplies and will act as a hub for delivery to other hospitals. Impact of strikes Teams that went to Al-Amal saw the aftermath of recent strikes that disabled the hospital’s radio tower and impacted the central ambulance dispatch system for the entire Khan Younis area, affecting more than 1.5 million people. Only five out of nine ambulances the hospital once had remain functioning. WHO staff reported that it was impossible to walk inside the hospital without stepping over patients and people seeking refuge. Furthermore, only a few functioning toilets are available in the hospital, adjacent community buildings and PRCS training centres. As they were transiting across Gaza, staff witnessed tens of thousands of people fleeing heavy strikes in the Khan Younis and Middle Area on foot, on donkeys, or in cars. Make-shift shelters were being built along the road. Overcrowding and disease fears WHO feared this new displacement will further strain health facilities in the south, which are already struggling to meet the immense needs. “This forced mass movement of people will also lead to more overcrowding, increased risk of infectious diseases, and make it even harder to deliver humanitarian aid,” said Dr Rik Peeperkorn, Representative for the West Bank and Gaza. Latest WHO assessments show that Gaza currently has 13 partially functioning hospitals and two minimally functioning ones, while 21 are not functioning at all. Facilities include Nasser Medical Complex, the most important referral hospital in southern Gaza, which is partially functioning, and recent reports of nearby residential areas being ordered to evacuate are extremely concerning. Personnel also reported that the need for food continues to be acute across the Gaza. Hungry people have been stopping convoys in the search for food. WHO said its ability to supply medicines, medical supplies, and fuel to hospitals is being increasingly constrained by the hunger and desperation of people both on the way to hospitals, and inside them. Ceasefire needed now Tedros stressed that the safety of WHO staff and continuity of operations depends on more food arriving in all of Gaza, immediately. Colleagues are also being directly and personally affected by the conflict, just like virtually everyone in Gaza, and he continues to receive heartbreaking news of losses. “The recent United Nations [Security Council](https://www.un.org/securitycouncil/) resolution appeared to provide hope of an improvement in humanitarian aid distribution within Gaza,” he added. “However, based on WHO eyewitness accounts on the ground, the resolution is tragically yet to have an impact. What we urgently need, right now, is a ceasefire to spare civilians from further violence and begin the long road towards reconstruction and peace.”

author: Telemadrid
title: La Supercopa de España femenina volverá a jugarse en Leganés
text: La Federación Española de Fútbol (RFEF) confirmó este jueves que el estadio Municipal de Butarque de Leganés volverá a acoger la Supercopa femenina del 22 al 26 de enero próximo, con la participación del Barcelona, la Real Sociedad, el Real Madrid y el Atlético de Madrid.La primera semifinal se jugará el miércoles día 22, a las 19.00 horas, entre el Barça, defensor del título además de campeón de Liga y de Copa de la Reina, y el Atlético de Madrid, tercer clasificado en el campeonato regular.TMDHTM20241226_0013La otra semifinal se jugará el jueves 23, igualmente a las 19.00 horas, y enfrentará al Real Madrid, subcampeón de Liga, y a la Real Sociedad, último subcampeón de la competición y también de la Copa. La final se disputará el domingo 26 de enero a las 12 horas.El estadio de Butarque fue inaugurado en 1998 con capacidad para algo más de 12.000 espectadores y fue escenario tanto de la edición de la Supercopa del año pasado como de la Copa de la Reina, además de acoger algunos partidos de la selección española.
